# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alfred-dregger
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in West Germany on 19 November 1972 to elect the members of the seventh Bundestag.
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] In the first snap elections since the resumption of democratic elections in 1949, the Social Democratic Party (SPD) emerged as the largest party in parliament, winning 230 of the 496 seats.
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] The SPD's Willy Brandt remained chancellor after resuming his coalition government with the Free Democratic Party.
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] On 27 April 1972 the opposition had tried to have CDU leader Rainer Barzel elected new chancellor in a constructive vote of no confidence, but Barzel surprisingly missed the majority of 249 by two votes.
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] Rumours that at least one member of the CDU/CSU faction had been paid by the East German *Stasi* to abstain (in effect, voting against Barzel) were confirmed by Markus Wolf, former head of the *Hauptverwaltung Aufklärung*, in 1997.
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] Nevertheless, the following budget debates revealed that the government's majority was lost and only the upcoming organisation of the 1972 Summer Olympics in Munich delayed the arrangement of new elections.
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] On 22 September 1972 Chancellor Brandt asked for a vote of confidence, which required the same majority of 249 "yes" votes: it failed with 233 "yes" votes to 246 "no" votes.
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] The members of the government did not participate (in effect, voting no) to ensure the vote would fail, however it would have regardless.
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] This allowed Brandt to advise President Gustav Heinemann to dissolve the Bundestag and call new elections the same day.
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] In the tense campaign, the CDU/CSU attacked Brandt as being too lenient towards Eastern Europe and having the wrong ideas on the economy.
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] SPD and FDP benefited from the enormous personal popularity of the chancellor, laureate of the 1971 Nobel Peace Prize.
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] He gained the support by numerous celebrities of the West German culture and media scene (e.g.
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] Günter Grass), expressed by the slogan *Willy wählen!* ("Vote for Willy!").
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] Voter turnout was 91.1%, the highest ever since 1949.
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] In 1970 the voting age had been lowered from 21 to 18.
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] The SPD celebrated their best result ever, representing the largest faction in the German parliament for the first time since the 1930 Reichstag elections.
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] It enabled the party to nominate Annemarie Renger for President of the Bundestag; she was the first Social Democrat and also the first woman to hold this office.
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] On 14 December 1972 the Bundestag MPs of the social-liberal coalition re-elected Willy Brandt chancellor.
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] His Cabinet Brandt II returned to government the next day, again with FDP chairman Walter Scheel as vice-chancellor and foreign minister.
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] Defeated Rainer Barzel resigned as CDU chairman on 9 May 1973; he was succeeded by Helmut Kohl.
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] On 7 May 1974, Brandt would resign in the course of the Guillaume Affair, after one of his personal aides had been unmasked as a *Stasi* agent.
[src:alfred-dregger/1972-west-german-federal-election] The coalition continued under his party fellow Helmut Schmidt, while Brandt remained SPD chairman until 1987.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in Germany on 27 September 1998 to elect the members of the 14th Bundestag.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] The Social Democratic Party (SPD) emerged as the largest faction in parliament for the first time since 1972, with its leader Gerhard Schröder becoming chancellor.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] The Christian Democrats had their worst election result since 1949.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] Since German reunification on 3 October 1990, the unemployment rate in Germany had risen from 4.2% to 9.4% in 1998, with the Federal Labor Office registering more than 4 million unemployed.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] The unified Germany had to fight economic and domestic difficulties even as it actively participated in the project of European integration.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] Most people blamed the centre-right coalition government of the Christian Democratic Union/Christian Social Union (CDU/CSU) and the Free Democratic Party (FDP) for the economic difficulties.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] Longtime Chancellor Helmut Kohl's government was regarded by many as not having fully implemented the unification after eight years, in view of the mass protests in many eastern German towns due to job losses and social welfare cuts.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] The 1998 campaign began with both the CDU and SPD working out who would lead their parties.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] There had been rumours that Kohl would resign and allow Wolfgang Schäuble to take the reins of the CDU, but these rumours were rendered obsolete when Kohl announced in April 1997 that he would seek the chancellorship for a sixth term.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] The two contenders for the SPD nomination were Oskar Lafontaine, the party's chairman, and Gerhard Schröder, Minister-President of Lower Saxony.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] On 1 March 1998, Schröder led the SPD to a huge victory in the Lower Saxony state election, gaining an unusual absolute majority for the second time and effectively receiving the SPD nomination for federal chancellor.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] Schröder had announced he would withdraw his bid for the nomination if he received below 42 percent of the popular vote.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] In the 1998 general elections, Schröder received 47.9 percent.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] Following this election, Lafontaine withdrew his bid and Schröder was inaugurated in the May 1998 convention.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] For the SPD, Schröder offered a new face for the party.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] He gave the party a new vigor, one that was lacking in the CDU after Kohl proclaimed his nomination.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] Many in the CDU questioned if Kohl had made the right choice for the party.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] The CDU campaign was based on the experience and reputation of Kohl.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] One of the CDU's main slogans was 'Safety, not Risks.' "Kohl exploited his familiarity and experience, as well as his status as Europe's longest serving head of government." The SPD on the other hand ran the campaign using strategies developed in the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD set up election headquarters and introduced 'rapid rebuttal units' not unlike those used by Bill Clinton of the United States in his successful presidential bid in 1992.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD avoided direct attacks at Kohl, but rather focused on their message of a "new center".
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] The FDP had usually ridden on the coattails of the CDU, and was mostly disapproved in the polls.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] With the SPD well ahead in the polls, many of the voters from the CDU had fewer incentives to vote for the FDP.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] The FDP was also having trouble projecting a coherent platform to voters.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] The Greens too were having issues concerning their platform.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] The two factions in the Greens, the fundamentalists and the pragmatists, had problems settling on their platform since the founding of the Green party.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] The major issue of the 1998 campaign was unemployment.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] In 1996, the unemployment rate in Germany surpassed the government's "limit" of 4 million unemployed people.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] Both parties blamed high labor costs, high taxes and the high welfare costs as the causes of the problem.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] During the campaign, Schröder used this issue against Kohl, calling him 'the unemployment chancellor.' Unemployment was worst in the former East Germany.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] While the national rate stood at 9.4 percent, former East Germany was suffering with unemployment at 20 percent.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] Many in the former East Germany blamed Kohl for the slow economic recovery.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] Another issue at hand were Germany's tax and welfare reforms.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] While the CDU/CSU had offered proposals to reduce benefits in healthcare and pensions, the SPD controlled Bundesrat secured the passage of the bill.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] The proposed bill also offered tax cuts that were to benefit the rich, something the SPD opposed.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] While Kohl continually pushed the issue of European integration, the issue fell short from voters' minds.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] Schröder, on the other hand, almost ignored the issue.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] Many voters in Germany had other concerns besides the European Union.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] Toward the end of the campaign, polls placed the CDU/CSU and FDP coalition in a tie with the SPD and Green coalition.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] Despite these polls, the final numbers told a different story.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD-Green coalition won an unexpectedly large victory, taking 345 seats and earning a strong majority in the Bundestag—the first centre-left absolute majority in post-World War II Germany.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD won 40.9 percent of the vote, due to an increase of 4.5 percent from 1994.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU-FDP coalition had gone into the election with a solid majority and 341 seats, but was cut down to 288 seats.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU lost 6.2% of its 1994 vote, and lost 109 electoral districts to the SPD.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] Germany's mixed-member proportional system, in which a slate of statewide delegates are elected alongside the electorate delegates, softened the blow somewhat, so the CDU/CSU only suffered a net loss of 49 seats.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] It was still the CDU/CSU's worst defeat ever.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] By contrast, their junior coalition partner, the FDP, netted a loss of just 4 seats.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] The SPD swept all single-member constituency seats in the states of Brandenburg, Saxony-Anhalt, Saarland, Bremen, Hamburg and (for the first and last time) Schleswig-Holstein.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] Kohl lost his own constituency of Ludwigshafen, though he was still re-elected to the Bundestag through the Rhineland-Palatinate CDU party list, and he had not won the seat in the 1983 and 1987 elections.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] Future Chancellor Angela Merkel only narrowly won her constituency of Stralsund – Rügen – Grimmen with only 37.3 percent of the vote; the only time she got less than 40 percent of the vote.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] A new government was formed by a coalition between the SPD and the Greens, with the SPD's Gerhard Schröder as chancellor and Greens leader Joschka Fischer as vice-chancellor and foreign minister.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] It was the first red-green coalition government at the federal level in Germany, as well as the first purely centre-left government in post-World War II Germany.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] Kohl stepped down as chairman of the CDU, as did CSU chairman Theodor Waigel.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] The 1998 German election was historic in many ways.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] It resulted in a centre-right government being succeeded by a left-wing one—the first in postwar Germany (the SPD's previous term in government had been at the helm of a centre-left coalition).
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] In addition, it brought to an end the sixteen-year rule of Kohl – the second-longest of any German chancellor, and the longest tenure for a democratically elected head of government in German history.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] It has been compared to the defeat of Winston Churchill in 1945 – both were seen as conservative wartime leaders, and in both cases both were turned out of office by the electorate once the war was over.
[src:alfred-dregger/1998-german-federal-election] Churchill was ousted before World War II was even over, while Kohl managed to hang onto power for two more terms after the reunification of Germany (which is often considered to be the end of the Cold War).
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The **20 July plot**, sometimes referred to as **Operation Valkyrie** (German: *Unternehmen Walküre*), was a failed attempt to assassinate Adolf Hitler, the dictator of Nazi Germany, and overthrow the Nazi government on 20 July 1944.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The plotters were part of the German resistance, mainly composed of *Wehrmacht* officers.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The principal mastermind of the conspiracy, Claus von Stauffenberg, tried to kill Hitler by detonating an explosive hidden in a briefcase.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] However, due to the location of the bomb at the time of detonation, the blast only dealt Hitler minor injuries.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The planners' subsequent *coup* attempt also failed and resulted in a purge of the *Wehrmacht*.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] As early as 1938, German military officers had plotted to overthrow Hitler, but indecisive leadership and the pace of global events stymied action.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Plotters gained a sense of urgency in 1943 after Germany lost the Battle of Stalingrad and Soviet forces began to push towards Germany.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Under the leadership of Stauffenberg, plotters tried to assassinate Hitler at least five times in 1943 and 1944.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] With the Nazi secret police, the Gestapo, closing in on the plotters, a final attempt was organised in July 1944.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Stauffenberg personally took a briefcase containing a block of plastic explosive to a conference in the Wolf's Lair.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The explosives were armed and placed next to Hitler, but it appears they were moved unwittingly at the last moment behind a table leg by Heinz Brandt, inadvertently saving Hitler's life.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] When the bomb detonated, it killed Brandt and two others, while the rest of the room's occupants were injured, one of whom, Rudolf Schmundt, later died from his injuries.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Hitler's trousers were singed by the blast, and he suffered a perforated eardrum and conjunctivitis, but was otherwise unharmed.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The plotters, unaware of their failure, then attempted a *coup d'état*.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] A few hours after the blast, the conspiracy used *Wehrmacht* units to take control of several cities, including Berlin, immediately after giving them disinformation on the intention of the orders they were given.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] This part of the coup d'état attempt is referred to by the name "Operation Valkyrie", which has also become associated with the entire event.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Within hours, the Nazi regime had reasserted its control of Germany.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] A few members of the conspiracy, including Stauffenberg, were executed by firing squad the same night.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] In the months after the *coup* attempt, the Gestapo arrested more than 7,000 people, 4,980 of whom were executed.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The apparent aim of the coup d'état attempt was to wrest political control of Germany and its armed forces from the Nazi Party (including the Schutzstaffel) and to make peace with the Western Allies as soon as possible.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The details of the conspirators' peace initiatives remain unknown.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Since 1938 there had been groups plotting an overthrow of some kind within the German Army and in the German Military Intelligence Organization.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] They soon established contacts with several prominent civilians, including Carl Goerdeler, the former mayor of Leipzig, and Helmuth James von Moltke, the great-grandnephew of Moltke the Elder, hero of the Franco-Prussian War.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Groups of military plotters exchanged ideas with civilian, political, and intellectual resistance groups in the Kreisauer Kreis (which met at the von Moltke estate in Kreisau) and in other secret circles.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Moltke was against killing Hitler; instead, he wanted him placed on trial.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Moltke said, "we are all amateurs and would only bungle it".
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Moltke also believed killing Hitler would be hypocritical: Hitler and National Socialism had turned wrongdoing into a system, something which the resistance should avoid.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] In 1942 a new conspiratorial group formed, led by Colonel Henning von Tresckow, a member of Field Marshal Fedor von Bock's staff, who commanded Army Group Centre in Operation Barbarossa.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Tresckow systematically recruited oppositionists into the Group's staff, making it the nerve centre of the army resistance.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Little could be done against Hitler as he was heavily guarded, and none of the plotters could get near enough to him.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] During 1942, Oster and Tresckow nevertheless succeeded in rebuilding an effective resistance network.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Their most important recruit was General Friedrich Olbricht, head of the General Army Office headquarters at the Bendlerblock in central Berlin, who controlled an independent system of communications to reserve units throughout Germany.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Linking this asset to Tresckow's resistance group in Army Group Centre created a viable coup apparatus.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] In late 1942 Tresckow and Olbricht formulated a plan to assassinate Hitler and stage an overthrow during Hitler's visit to the headquarters of Army Group Centre at Smolensk in March 1943, by placing a bomb on his plane (Operation Spark).
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The bomb failed to detonate, and a second attempt a week later with Hitler at an exhibition of captured Soviet weaponry in Berlin also failed.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] These failures demoralised the conspirators.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] During 1943 Tresckow tried without success to recruit senior army field commanders such as Field Marshal Erich von Manstein and Field Marshal Gerd von Rundstedt, to support a seizure of power.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Tresckow, in particular, worked on his Commander-in-Chief of Army Group Centre, Field Marshal Günther von Kluge, to persuade him to move against Hitler and at times succeeded in gaining his consent, only to find him indecisive at the last minute.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] However, despite their refusals, none of the Field Marshals reported their treasonous activities to the Gestapo or Hitler.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] While the primary goal of the plotters was to remove Hitler from power, they did so for various reasons.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The majority of the group behind the 20 July plot were conservative nationalists—idealists, but not necessarily of a democratic stripe.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Martin Borschat portrays their motivations as a matter of aristocratic resentment, writing that the plot was mainly carried out by conservative elites who were initially integrated by the Nazi government but during the war lost their influence and were concerned about regaining it.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] However, at least in Stauffenberg's case, the conviction that Nazi Germany's atrocities against civilians and prisoners of war were a dishonour to the nation and its military was likely a major motivating factor.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Historian Judith Michel assesses the circle around the 20 July Group as a diverse and heterogeneous group that included liberal democrats, conservatives, social democrats, authoritarian aristocrats, and even communists.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The common goal was to overthrow Hitler's regime and bring the war to a swift end.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] There is evidence of the plot encompassing a broad spectrum of plotters which included communists.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] That April, before the attempted coup, Stauffenberg agreed to cooperate with the Operational Leadership of the KPD (Communist Party of Germany) remaining in Germany.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Contacts were established through the Social Democrats Adolf Reichwein and Julius Leber.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Among demands initially countenanced by the plotters for issue towards the Allies were such points as re-establishment of Germany's 1914 boundaries with Belgium, France and Poland and no reparations.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] They believed that Europe should be controlled under German hegemony.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The overall goals towards Poland were mixed within the plotters.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Most of the plotters found it desirable to restore the old German borders of 1914, while others pointed out that the demands were unrealistic, and amendments had to be made.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Some like Friedrich-Werner Graf von der Schulenburg even wanted all of Poland annexed to Germany.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] To Poland, which was fighting against Nazi Germany with both its army and government in exile, the territorial demands and traditional nationalistic visions of resistance were not much different from the racist policies of Hitler.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Stauffenberg, one of the leaders of the plot, stated in 1939 during the Poland campaign, five years before the *coup* attempt: "It is essential that we begin a systemic colonisation in Poland.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Many members of the plot had helped the Nazis to gain power and shared revisionist foreign policy goals pursued by Hitler, and even at the time of the plot were anti-democratic, hoping to replace Hitler with a conservative-authoritarian government involving aristocratic rule.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] They opposed popular legitimation or mass participation in governance of the state.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Commencement of peace negotiations with the Western Allies, punishment of those Germans responsible for the Second World War.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] By mid-1943 the tide of war was turning decisively against Germany.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The army plotters and their civilian allies became convinced that Hitler should be assassinated, so that a government acceptable to the western Allies could be formed, and a separate peace negotiated in time to prevent a Soviet invasion of Germany.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] In August 1943 Tresckow met, for the first time, a young staff officer named Lieutenant Colonel Claus von Stauffenberg.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Severely wounded in North Africa, Stauffenberg was a political conservative and zealous German nationalist.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] From early 1942, he had come to share two basic convictions with many military officers: that Germany was being led to disaster and that Hitler's removal from power was necessary.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] After the Battle of Stalingrad in December 1942, despite his religious scruples, he concluded that the Führer's assassination was a lesser moral evil than Hitler's remaining in power.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Stauffenberg brought a new tone of decisiveness to the ranks of the resistance movement.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] When Tresckow was assigned to the Eastern Front, Stauffenberg took charge of planning and executing the assassination attempt.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Olbricht now put forward a new strategy for staging a coup against Hitler.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Olbricht suggested that this plan could be used to mobilise the Reserve Army for the purpose of the coup.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] In August and September 1943, Tresckow drafted the "revised" Valkyrie plan and new supplementary orders.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] A secret declaration began with these words: "The Führer Adolf Hitler is dead!
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Previously, it was believed that Stauffenberg was mainly responsible for the Valkyrie plan, but documents recovered by the Soviet Union after the war and released in 2007 suggest that the plan was developed by Tresckow by late 1943.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] All written information was handled by Tresckow's wife, Erika, and by Margarethe von Oven, his secretary.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Both women wore gloves to avoid leaving fingerprints.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] On at least two other occasions Tresckow had tried to assassinate the Führer.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The first plan was to shoot him during dinner at the army base camp, but this plan was aborted because it was widely believed that Hitler wore a bullet-proof vest.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The conspirators also considered poisoning him, but this was not possible because his food was specially prepared and tasted.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] They concluded that a time bomb was the only option.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Operation Valkyrie could only be put into effect by Hitler himself, or by General Friedrich Fromm, commander of the Reserve Army, so the latter had to be either won over to the conspiracy or in some way neutralised if the plan was to succeed.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] As the war situation deteriorated, Hitler no longer appeared in public and rarely visited Berlin.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] He spent most of his time at his headquarters at the *Wolfsschanze* near Rastenburg in East Prussia, with occasional breaks at his Bavarian mountain retreat Obersalzberg near Berchtesgaden.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] In both places, he was heavily guarded and rarely saw people he did not know or trust.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Himmler and the *Gestapo* were increasingly suspicious of plots against Hitler and rightly suspected the officers of the General Staff, which was indeed the source of many conspiracies against him.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] By mid-1944 the *Gestapo* was closing in on the conspirators.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Even if it fails, we must take action in Berlin ⁠,⁠ ⁠for the practical purpose no longer matters; what matters now is that the German resistance movement must take the plunge before the eyes of the world and of history.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Nothing came of this meeting, but Popitz was not arrested and Himmler apparently did nothing to track down the resistance network which he knew was operating within the state bureaucracy.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] It is possible that Himmler, who by late 1943 knew that the war was unwinnable, allowed the plot to go ahead in the knowledge that if it succeeded he would be Hitler's successor, and could then bring about a peace settlement.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Popitz was not alone in seeing Himmler as a potential ally.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] General von Bock advised Tresckow to seek his support, but there is no evidence that he did so.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Goerdeler was apparently also in indirect contact with Himmler via a mutual acquaintance, Carl Langbehn.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Wilhelm Canaris's biographer Heinz Höhne suggests that Canaris and Himmler were working together to bring about a change of regime, but this remains speculation.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] On Saturday 1 July 1944 Stauffenberg was appointed Chief of Staff to General Friedrich Fromm at the Reserve Army headquarters on Bendlerstraße in central Berlin.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] This position enabled Stauffenberg to attend Hitler's military conferences, either at the *Wolfsschanze* in East Prussia or at Berchtesgaden, and would thus give him an opportunity, perhaps the last that would present itself, to kill Hitler with a bomb or a pistol.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Meanwhile, new key allies had been gained.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] These included General Carl-Heinrich von Stülpnagel, the German military commander in France, who would take control in Paris when Hitler was killed, and it was hoped, negotiate an immediate armistice with the invading Allied armies.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] On 7 July 1944 General Helmuth Stieff was to kill Hitler at a display of new uniforms at Klessheim castle near Salzburg.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] However, Stieff felt unable to kill Hitler.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Stauffenberg now decided to do both, assassinate Hitler and to manage the plot in Berlin.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] In fact, it was unusual for Himmler to attend military conferences.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] By 15 July, when Stauffenberg again flew to the *Wolfsschanze*, this condition had been dropped.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The plan was for Stauffenberg to plant the briefcase with the bomb in Hitler's conference room with a timer running, excuse himself from the meeting, wait for the explosion, then fly back to Berlin and join the other plotters at the Bendlerblock.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Operation Valkyrie would be mobilised, the Reserve Army would take control of Germany and the other Nazi leaders would be arrested.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Beck would be appointed provisional head of state, Goerdeler would be chancellor, and Witzleben would be commander-in-chief of the armed forces.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Again on 15 July, the attempt was called off at the last minute.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Himmler and Göring were present, but Hitler was called out of the room at the last moment.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Stauffenberg was able to intercept the bomb and prevent its discovery.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] On the morning of Thursday 20 July Stauffenberg flew back to the *Wolfsschanze* for another military conference at which Hitler would be present, once again with a bomb in his briefcase.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] At around 12:30 pm as the conference began, Stauffenberg asked to use a washroom in Wilhelm Keitel's office, saying that he had to change his shirt, which indeed was soaked through with sweat, it being a very hot day.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] There, assisted by von Haeften, he used pliers to crush the end of a pencil detonator inserted into a 1 kilogram (2.2 lb) block of plastic explosive wrapped in brown paper, that was prepared by Wessel von Freytag-Loringhoven.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The pencil detonator consisted of a thin copper tube containing cupric chloride that would take about ten minutes to silently eat through wire holding back the firing pin from the percussion cap.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] It was slow going due to war wounds that had cost Stauffenberg an eye, his right hand, and two fingers on his left hand.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Interrupted by a guard knocking on the door advising him that the meeting was about to begin, he was not able to prime the second bomb, which he gave to his aide-de-camp, Werner von Haeften.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Stauffenberg placed the single primed bomb inside his briefcase and, with the unwitting assistance of Major Ernst John von Freyend, entered the conference room containing Hitler and 20 officers, positioning the briefcase under the table near Hitler.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] After a few minutes, Stauffenberg received a planned telephone call and left the room.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] At 12:42 the bomb detonated, demolishing the conference room and killing a stenographer instantly.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] More than 20 people in the room were injured with three officers later dying.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Hitler survived, as did everyone else who was shielded from the blast by the conference table leg.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] His trousers were singed and tattered, and he suffered from a perforated eardrum (as did most of the other 24 people in the room), as well as from conjunctivitis in his right eye.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Hitler's personal physician, Theodor Morell, administered penicillin which had been taken from captured Allied soldiers for treatment; Morell had previously observed the death of Reinhard Heydrich from sepsis in an assassination two years earlier.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Stauffenberg was seen leaving the conference building by Kurt Salterberg, a soldier on guard duty who did not consider this out of the ordinary as attendees sometimes left to collect documents.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] He then saw a "massive" cloud of smoke, wood splinters and paper and men being hurled through a window and door.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Stauffenberg, upon witnessing the explosion and smoke, assumed that Hitler was dead.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] He then climbed into a staff car with his aide Werner von Haeften and managed to bluff his way past three checkpoints to exit the *Wolfsschanze* complex.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Haeften then tossed the second (unprimed) bomb into the forest as they made a dash for Rastenburg airfield, reaching it before it could be realised that Stauffenberg could be responsible for the explosion.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] At first it was thought that the explosion had been the result of an aerial bombing, but when it was confirmed that no warplanes had flown over and Stauffenberg was absent, the theory of an assassination attempt gained strength.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] By 13:00 he was airborne in a Heinkel He 111 arranged by General Eduard Wagner.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] By the time Stauffenberg's aircraft reached Berlin about 16:00, General Erich Fellgiebel, an officer at the *Wolfsschanze* who was in on the plot, had phoned the Bendlerblock and told the plotters that Hitler had survived the explosion.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] As a result, the plot to mobilise Operation Valkyrie would have no chance of succeeding once the officers of the Reserve Army knew that Hitler was alive.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] There was more confusion when Stauffenberg's aircraft landed and he phoned from the airport to say that Hitler *was* in fact dead.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The Bendlerblock plotters did not know whom to believe.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Finally, at 16:00 Olbricht issued the orders for Operation Valkyrie to be mobilised.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The vacillating General Fromm, however, phoned Field Marshal Wilhelm Keitel at the Wolf's Lair and was assured that Hitler was alive.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Keitel demanded to know Stauffenberg's whereabouts.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] This told Fromm that the plot had been traced to his headquarters and that he was in mortal danger.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Fromm replied that he thought Stauffenberg was with Hitler.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Meanwhile, General Carl-Heinrich von Stülpnagel, military governor of occupied France, managed to disarm the SD and SS and captured most of their leadership.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] He travelled to Field Marshal Günther von Kluge's headquarters and asked him to contact the Allies, only to be informed that Hitler was alive.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] At 16:40 Stauffenberg and Haeften arrived at the Bendlerblock.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Fromm, presumably to protect himself, changed sides and attempted to have Stauffenberg arrested.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Olbricht and Stauffenberg restrained him at gunpoint and Olbricht then appointed General Erich Hoepner to take over his duties.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] By this time Himmler had taken charge of the situation and had issued orders countermanding Olbricht's mobilisation of Operation Valkyrie.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] In many places the coup was going ahead, led by officers who believed that Hitler was dead.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] City Commandant, and conspirator, Lieutenant General Paul von Hase ordered the *Wachbataillon Großdeutschland*, under the command of Major Otto Ernst Remer, to secure the Wilhelmstraße and arrest Propaganda Minister Joseph Goebbels.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] In Vienna, Prague, and many other places troops occupied Nazi Party offices and arrested Gauleiters and SS officers.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] At around 18:10, the commander of Military District III (Berlin), General Joachim von Kortzfleisch, was summoned to the Bendlerblock; he angrily refused Olbricht's orders, kept shouting "the Führer is alive", was arrested, and held under guard.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] General Karl Freiherr von Thüngen was appointed in his place but proved to be of almost no help.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] General Fritz Lindemann, who was supposed to make a proclamation to the German people over the radio, failed to appear and as he held the only copy, Beck had to work on a new one.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] At 19:00 Hitler was sufficiently recovered to make phone calls.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] He called Goebbels at the Propaganda Ministry.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Goebbels arranged for Hitler to speak to Major Otto Ernst Remer, commander of the troops surrounding the Ministry.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] After assuring him that he was still alive, Hitler ordered Remer to regain control of the situation in Berlin and capture the conspirators alive.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Major Remer ordered his troops to surround and seal off the Bendlerblock, but not to enter the buildings.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] At 20:00 a furious Witzleben arrived at the Bendlerblock and had a bitter argument with Stauffenberg, who was still insisting that the coup could go ahead.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] At around this time the planned seizure of power in Paris was aborted when Field Marshal Günther von Kluge, who had recently been appointed commander-in-chief in the West, learnt that Hitler was alive.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] As Remer regained control of the city and word spread that Hitler was still alive, the less resolute members of the conspiracy in Berlin began to change sides.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Fromm was freed from his room and fighting broke out in the Bendlerblock between officers supporting and opposing the coup; Stauffenberg was wounded after a shootout.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] As the fighting was still ongoing, Remer and his forces arrived at the Bendlerblock and the conspirators were overwhelmed and arrested; by 23:00 Fromm and Remer had regained control of the building.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] At first Beck only seriously wounded himself—he was then shot in the neck and killed by soldiers.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Despite protests from Remer (who had been ordered by Hitler to arrest the conspirators), at 00:10 on 21 July the four officers were executed in the courtyard outside, possibly to prevent them from revealing Fromm's involvement.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Others would have been executed as well, but at 00:30 *Waffen-SS* personnel led by SS-*Obersturmbannführer* Otto Skorzeny arrived and further executions were forbidden.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Over the following weeks, Himmler's *Gestapo*, driven by a furious Hitler, rounded up nearly everyone who had the remotest connection with the plot.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The discovery of letters and diaries in the homes and offices of those arrested revealed the plots of 1938, 1939, and 1943, and this led to further rounds of arrests, including that of Colonel General Franz Halder, who finished the war in a concentration camp.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Under Himmler's new *Sippenhaft* (blood guilt) laws, many relatives of the principal plotters were also arrested in the immediate aftermath of the failed plot.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Particularly noteworthy in considering this issue is the scientific publication of Robert Loeffel.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] In his study, Loeffel came to the conclusion that *Sippenhaft*, as part of state terror at the end of the war, was a means of intimidation within Nazi Germany, when in reality this practice was not always applied, and most of the terror was adopted only after 20 July.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] This was due to its duality: terror was implemented only in quantities necessary to maintain a level of fear among the population that would not lead them to go over to the side of resistance.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] More than 7,000 people were arrested and 4,980 were executed.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Not all of them were connected with the plot, since the *Gestapo* used the occasion to settle scores with many other people suspected of opposition sympathies.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Allied radio stations also speculated on who the possible remaining suspects could be, many of whom were eventually implicated in the plot.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Very few of the plotters tried to escape or to deny their guilt when arrested.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Those who survived interrogation were given perfunctory trials before the People's Court, a kangaroo court that always decided in favour of the prosecution.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The court's president, Roland Freisler, was a fanatical Nazi seen shouting furiously and insulting the accused in the trial, which was filmed for propaganda purposes.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The plotters were stripped of their uniforms and given old, shabby clothing to humiliate them for the cameras.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The officers involved in the plot were "tried" before the Court of Military Honour, a drumhead court-martial that merely considered the evidence furnished to it by the *Gestapo* before expelling the accused from the Army in disgrace and handing them over to the People's Court.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The first trials were held on 7 and 8 August 1944 and were held in the plenary chamber of the Berlin high court the Kammergericht in Schöneberg.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Hitler had ordered that those found guilty should be "hanged like cattle".
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Many people took their own lives prior to either their trial or their execution, including Kluge, who was accused of having knowledge of the plot beforehand and not revealing it to Hitler.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Stülpnagel tried to commit suicide, but survived and was hanged.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Tresckow killed himself the day after the failed plot by use of a hand grenade in no man's land between Soviet and German lines.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Fromm's attempt to win favour by executing Stauffenberg and others on the night of 20 July had merely exposed his own previous lack of action and apparent failure to report the plot.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Having been arrested on 21 July, Fromm was later convicted and sentenced to death by the People's Court.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Despite his knowledge of the conspiracy, his formal sentence charged him with poor performance in his duties.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] He was executed in Brandenburg an der Havel.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Hitler personally commuted his death sentence from hanging to the "more honourable" firing squad.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Erwin Planck, the son of the physicist Max Planck, was executed for his involvement.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] A report of SS-*Obergruppenführer* Ernst Kaltenbrunner to Hitler dated 29 November 1944 on the background of the plot states that the Pope was somehow a conspirator, specifically naming Eugenio Pacelli, Pope Pius XII, as being a party in the attempt.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] A member of the SA convicted of participating in the plot was SA-*Obergruppenführer* Wolf-Heinrich Graf von Helldorf, who was the *Orpo* Police Chief of Berlin and had been in contact with members of the resistance since before the war.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Collaborating closely with SS-*Gruppenführer* Arthur Nebe, he was supposed to direct all police forces in Berlin to stand down and not interfere in the military actions to seize the government.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] However, his actions on 20 July had minimal influence on the events.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] For his involvement in the conspiracy, he was later arrested, convicted of treason and executed.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] After 3 February 1945, when Freisler was killed in an American air raid, there were no more formal trials, but as late as April, with the war weeks away from its end, Canaris' diary was found, and many more people were implicated.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Hans Von Dohnanyi was accused of being the "spiritual leader" of the conspiracy to assassinate Hitler, and executed on 6 April 1945.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Dietrich Bonhoeffer, whom Von Dohnanyi had recruited into the Abwehr, was executed 9 April 1945 along with Canaris, Oster, and four others.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Executions continued and ramped up into the last days of the war, as the Nazis were determined to take down as many of their enemies with them as they possibly could.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Hitler took his survival to be a "divine moment in history", and commissioned a special decoration to be made for each person wounded or killed in the blast.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The result was the Wound Badge of 20 July 1944.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The badges were struck in three values: gold, silver, and black.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] (The colours denoted the severity of the wounds received by each recipient.) A total of 100 badges were manufactured, and 47 are believed to have actually been awarded.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Each badge was accompanied by an ornate award document personally signed by Hitler.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The badges themselves bore a facsimile of his signature, making them among the rarest decorations to have been awarded by Nazi Germany.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] For his role in stopping the coup Major Remer was promoted to colonel and ended the war as a Major General.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] After the war he co-founded the Socialist Reich Party and remained a prominent neo-Nazi and advocate of Holocaust denial until his death in 1997.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Major Philipp von Boeselager, the German officer who provided the plastic explosives used in the bomb, escaped detection and survived the war.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] He was the second-to-last survivor of those involved in the plot and died on 1 May 2008, aged 90.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The last survivor of the 20 July Plot was *Oberleutnant* Ewald-Heinrich von Kleist-Schmenzin, the thwarted plotter of just a few months before.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The conspirators had earlier designated positions in secret to form a government that would take office after the assassination of Hitler were it to prove successful.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Because of the plot's failure, such a government never rose to power and most of its members were executed.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Also, Andreas Hermes became chairman of the food committee in the Bizonal Economic Council after the war, but this was a role analogous to a parliamentary committee chairman rather than a government minister.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] It was planned to include one Austrian politician (probably Heinrich Gleißner or Karl Seitz) as minister without portfolio to keep Austria in the Reich.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Albert Speer was listed in several notes of the conspirators as a possible Minister of Armaments; however, most of these notes stated Speer should not be approached until after Hitler was dead and one conjectural government chart had a question mark beside Speer's name.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] This (in addition to Speer being one of Hitler's closest and most trusted friends) most likely saved Speer from arrest by the SS.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Wilhelm, Crown Prince of Germany, was also under suspicion as he was touted to be head of state after Hitler.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] He was placed under the supervision of the *Gestapo* and his home in the Cecilienhof at Potsdam watched.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The extent of Generalfeldmarschall Erwin Rommel's involvement in the military's resistance against Hitler or the 20 July plot is difficult to ascertain, as most of the leaders who were directly involved did not survive and limited documentation on the conspirators' plans and preparations exists.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Historians' opinions on this matter vary greatly.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] According to Peter Hoffmann, he had turned into Hitler's resolute opponent and in the end supported the coup (though not the assassination itself).
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] He was even the natural leader of the opposition in France to some extent, considering the fact he had drawn many military and political personnel into his orbit in preparation of a "Western solution".
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Ralf Georg Reuth thinks that the conspirators perhaps mistook Rommel's ambiguous attitude for approval of the assassination.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] In this regard, it should be remembered that the conspirators normally did not explicitly mention the assassination.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Rommel for his part was in fact both very naive and very attached to Hitler (who was the personification of National Socialism, which had provided Rommel with a great career).
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Thus even if Caesar von Hofacker—personal advisor to Stülpnagel— had mentioned a violent upheaval in Berlin, Rommel would perhaps not have interpreted it as an assassination.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Thus, Rommel's participation remains ambiguous and the perception of it largely has its source in the subsequent events (especially Rommel's forced suicide) and the accounts by surviving participants.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] According to a post-war account by Karl Strölin, the *Oberbürgermeister* of Stuttgart at that time, he and two other conspirators, Alexander von Falkenhausen and Carl Heinrich von Stülpnagel began efforts to bring Rommel into the anti-Hitler conspiracy in early 1944.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] On 15 April 1944 Rommel's new chief of staff, Hans Speidel, arrived in Normandy and reintroduced Rommel to Stülpnagel.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Speidel had previously been connected to Carl Goerdeler, the civilian leader of the resistance, but not to the plotters led by Stauffenberg, and only came to the attention of Stauffenberg due to his appointment to Rommel's headquarters.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The conspirators felt they needed the support of a field marshal on active duty.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Witzleben was a field marshal, but had not been on active duty since 1942.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] The conspirators gave instructions to Speidel to bring Rommel into their circle.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Speidel met with the former foreign minister Konstantin von Neurath and Strölin on 27 May in Germany, ostensibly at Rommel's request, although the latter was not present.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Neurath and Strölin suggested opening immediate surrender negotiations in the West, and, according to Speidel, Rommel agreed to further discussions and preparations.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Around the same timeframe, however, the plotters in Berlin were not aware that Rommel had reportedly decided to take part in the conspiracy.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] On 16 May, they informed Allen Dulles, through whom they hoped to negotiate with the Western Allies, that Rommel could not be counted on for support.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Three days before the assassination attempt, on 17 July, Rommel's staff car was strafed by an Allied aircraft in France; he was hospitalised with major injuries and incapacitated on 20 July.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] After the war, his widow maintained that he believed an assassination attempt would spark a civil war.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] According to the journalist and author William L.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Shirer, Rommel knew about the conspiracy and advocated that Hitler be arrested and placed on trial.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Evans concluded that he knew of a plot, but was not involved.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] What is not debated are the results of the failed bomb plot of 20 July.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Many conspirators were arrested and the dragnet expanded to thousands.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Consequently, it did not take long for Rommel to come under suspicion.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] He was primarily implicated through his connection to Kluge.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Rommel's name also came up in confessions made under torture by Stülpnagel and Hofacker, and was included in Goerdeler's papers on a list of potential supporters.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Hofacker confessed that Rommel had agreed to demand for Hitler to step down, and if he refused, Rommel would join the other conspirators in deposing Hitler.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Rommel was also planned to become a member of the post-Hitler government in papers drawn up by Goerdeler.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Hitler knew it would cause a major scandal on the home front to have the popular Rommel publicly branded as a traitor.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] With this in mind, he opted to give Rommel the option of suicide via cyanide or a public trial by Freisler's People's Court.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] Rommel was well aware that being hauled before the People's Court was tantamount to a death sentence.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] He also knew that if he chose to stand trial, his family would have been severely punished even before the all-but-certain conviction and execution.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] With this in mind, he committed suicide on 14 October 1944.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p01] He was buried with full military honours and his family was spared from persecution; his cause of death did not come to light until after the war.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p02] Involvement of the plotters in war crimes and atrocities has been studied by historians such as Christian Gerlach.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p02] Gerlach proved that plotters such as Tresckow and Gersdorff were aware of mass murder happening in the East from at least 1941.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p02] Tresckow also "signed orders for the deportation of thousands of orphaned children for forced labor in the Reich"—the so-called *Heu-Aktion*.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p02] Such actions led historians to question the motives of the plotters, which seemed more concerned with the military situation than with Nazi atrocities and German war crimes.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p02] However some others assert that, in such actions, Tresckow had to act out of principle to continue with his coup plans.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p02] Gerlach pointed out that the plotters had "selective moral criteria" and while they were concerned about Jews being exterminated in the Holocaust, they were far less disturbed about mass murder of civilians in the East.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p02] To Gerlach, the primary motivation of the plotters was to ensure German victory in the war or at least prevent defeat.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p02] Gerlach's arguments were later supported by the historian Hans Mommsen, who stated that the plotters were interested above all in military victory.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p02] However, Gerlach's arguments were also criticised by some scholars, among them Peter Hoffmann from McGill University and Klaus Jochen Arnold from the Konrad-Adenauer-Stiftung.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p02] While acknowledging that Tresckow and other 20 July conspirators had been involved in war crimes, Arnold writes that Gerlach's argument is oversimplified.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p02] In 2011 Danny Orbach, a Harvard University-based historian, wrote that Gerlach's reading of the sources is highly skewed, and, at times, diametrically opposed to what they actually say.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p02] In one case, according to Orbach, Gerlach had falsely paraphrased the memoir of the resistance fighter Colonel Rudolf Christoph Freiherr von Gersdorff, and in another case, quoted misleadingly from an SS document.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p02] The "first official memorial service for the resistance fighters of 20 July" was held on the tenth anniversary in 1954.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p02] The first all-German commemoration of the event did not take place until 1990.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p02] In 2013 the last surviving member of the plot, Ewald-Heinrich von Kleist-Schmenzin, died in Munich.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p02] As of 2014, the resistance fighters are generally considered heroes in Germany, according to *Deutsche Welle*.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p02] In 1989, American Gothic Rock band Christian Death released a song entitled ”Nazi Killer” about this assassination attempt.
[src:alfred-dregger/20-july-plot-p02] The song was featured on their album All the Love All the Hate (Part Two: All the Hate).
[src:alfred-dregger/achim-großmann] After graduating from high school in 1966 at the Kaiser-Karls-Gymnasium in Aachen, Großmann studied psychology at the TH Aachen, which he completed in 1972 with a diploma in psychology.
[src:alfred-dregger/achim-großmann] He then worked as an educational consultant at the advice center for parents, children and young people in Alsdorf until 1986, and as its director since 1979.
[src:alfred-dregger/achim-großmann] At the same time, he worked for several semesters as a lecturer in administrative psychology at the University of Applied Sciences for Public Administration in Aachen.
[src:alfred-dregger/achim-großmann] Achim Großmann was divorced and had two children.
[src:alfred-dregger/achim-großmann] From 1975 to 1998, Großmann was a councilor for the city of Würselen.
[src:alfred-dregger/achim-großmann] After the 1998 federal election, he was appointed Parliamentary State Secretary to the Federal Minister for Transport, Construction and Housing in the Government led by Gerhard Schröder.
[src:alfred-dregger/achim-großmann] After the formation of the Grand Coalition under Chancellor Angela Merkel, the ministry was renamed the Federal Ministry of Transport, Building and Urban Development.
[src:alfred-dregger/achim-großmann] After the 2009 federal election and the subsequent change in government, Großmann left office in October 2009.
[src:alfred-dregger/achim-großmann] In his eleven years in office, he served under five different construction and transport ministers.
[src:alfred-dregger/achim-großmann] As Parliamentary State Secretary, Achim Großmann was a member of the supervisory board of Deutsche Bahn and was involved in the preparations for the IPO.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] It was intended that he should study Protestant theology, but from 1798 he devoted himself in Göttingen to the study of law, philosophy, and natural science.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] Returning to Berlin, he was persuaded by his friend Friedrich von Gentz to take up political science.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] He had early formed a close intimacy with Gentz, his elder by 15 years; and this connection exercised an important influence both on his material circumstances and his mental development in after life.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] The two men differed widely in character and in their fundamental principles, but agreed, at least in their later period, in their practical political aims, and the friendship was only terminated by death.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] Müller worked for some time as referendary in the *Kurmärkische Kammer* in Berlin.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] Müller's relations with the Junker party and his co-operation with them in their opposition to Hardenberg's reforms made any public employment in Prussia impossible for him.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] He travelled in Sweden and Denmark, spent about two years in Poland, and then went to Vienna, where he was converted to the Catholic faith on 30 April 1805.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] Through Gentz he became acquainted with Metternich, to whom he was useful in the preparation of state papers.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] Via Poland, Müller traveled to Dresden, where he held lectures on German science and literature (1806), in which he showed himself to be a follower of Schlegel's romanticism.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] From 1806 to 1809, he lived at Dresden occupied in the political education of Prince Bernhard of Saxe-Weimar and lecturer on German literature, dramatic art, and political science.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] In 1808 he edited with Heinrich von Kleist the periodical *Phoebus*.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] In 1809, he returned to Berlin, and in 1811 to Vienna, where he lived in the house of Archduke Maximilian of Austria-Este and became the friend of Clemens Maria Hofbauer.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] He developed his central political ideas in his 1808/09 lectures, which he published in 1809 under the title *The Elements of Statecraft*.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] Even later he repeatedly criticized modern economic life.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] In 1809, after marrying Sophie von Haza-Radlitz, Müller went to Berlin, where he gave further historical-political lectures and published articles in the *Berliner Abendblatt* newspaper (1810/11) edited by Heinrich von Kleist.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] Müller, now back in the Prussian civil service, rejected the reform efforts of Karl August von Hardenberg, the state chancellor who had been in office since 1810, and tried to trigger a public discussion about the reform policy with his articles critical of the government.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] In 1811 he also acted as a close political adviser to the leader of the Prussian nobility opposition, Friedrich August Ludwig von der Marwitz.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] But Hardenberg smashed the opposition: Marwitz was imprisoned, the “Abendblatt” had to cease publication and Müller was deported to Vienna as a diplomatic reporter.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] Driven back to Berlin by the war, Müller drafted a bill of indictment against the state chancellor von Hardenberg on behalf of the Kurbrandenburgische Ritterschaft after the latter had refused Müller's request for employment in the civil service.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] In this indictment, intended for the king, he accused the chancellor of revolutionary principles.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] In 1813, he entered the Austrian service, and was appointed imperial commissioner and major of the rifle corps in Tyrol.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] He took part in the wars for liberation, and later on, as counsellor of the government, in the reorganization of the country.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] In 1815 he was called to Vienna, and went to Paris with the imperial staff.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] On the conclusion of peace, he became Austrian consul-general for Saxony at Leipzig, and agent for Anhalt and Schwarzburg.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] He edited here the periodicals *Deutscher Staatsanzeiger* (1816–1818) and *Unparteiischer Literatur- und Kirchenkorrespondent*.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] He attended the ministerial conferences at Carlsbad and Vienna (1819–1820), where, being one of the principal literary instruments of the reaction, he took part in framing the Carlsbad resolutions.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] In 1826, at the instance of Prince von Metternich, he was ennobled as **Ritter von Nittersdorf**, was recalled to Vienna (1827), appointed imperial counsellor, and employed in the service of the chancellery.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] Müller was distinguished as a writer not only on politics and economics, but on literature and aesthetics.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] His chief work is the **Elemente der Staatskunst** (*Elements of Statecraft*), originating in lectures delivered before Prince Bernhard of Saxe-Weimar and an assembly of politicians and diplomats at Dresden in the winter, 1808–09.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] It treats in six books of the state, of right, of the spirit of legislation in antiquity and in the Middle Ages, of money and national wealth, of the economical factors of the state and trade, of the relation between the state and religion.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] Müller was a conservative writer whose vision of the state was one of an absolute power, in contrast to theorists who emphasized the rights of man such as Montesquieu and Rousseau.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] Müller endeavoured to comprehend the connection between political and social science, and, while using the historical method, to base them upon philosophy and religion.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] With Edmund Burke, Friedrich von Gentz, Joseph de Maistre, and Karl Ludwig von Haller, he must be reckoned among the chief opponents of revolutionary ideas in politics.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] His ideal is medieval feudalism, on which the reorganization of modern political institutions should be modelled.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] In the field of literature and aesthetics, Müller belongs to the Romantic school.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] He is a Romanticist even in his specialty, politics and political economy.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] As Eichendorff says in his *Geschichte der poetischen Literatur Deutschlands* (new ed., by W.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] His position in political economy is defined by his strong opposition to Adam Smith's system of materialistic-liberal (so-called classical) political economy, or the so-called industry system.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] He censures Smith as presenting a one-sidedly material and individualistic conception of society, and as being too exclusively English in his views.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] Müller opposed free trade and strongly supported autarky.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] In contrast with the economical individualism of Adam Smith, he emphasizes the ethical element in national economy, the duty of the state toward the individual, and the religious basis which is also necessary in this field.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] Müller's importance in the history of political economy is acknowledged even by the opponents of his religious and political point of view.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] His reaction against Adam Smith, says Roscher (*Geschichte der National-Ökonomik*, p.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] 763), "is not blind or hostile, but is important, and often truly helpful." Some of his ideas, freed from much of their alloy, are reproduced in the writings of the historical school of German economists.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] One of Müller's main contributions to economic theory was his book "Versuch einer neuen Theorie des Geldes" (Attempt at a New Theory of Money), published in 1816.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] In this book, Müller defended paper money over metallic money, on the grounds that the "word" or stamp is what gives something a status as money, not the value of the material of which it is composed.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] Müller called this legitimating word or stamp "ideal money", and believed it to be the "'condition of possibility' of money as such".
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] The reactionary and feudalistic thought in Müller's writings, which agreed so little with the spirit of the times, prevented his political ideas from exerting a more notable and lasting influence on his age, while their religious character prevented them from being justly appreciated.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] However, Müller's teachings had long-term effects in that they were taken up again by 20th century theorists of corporatism and the corporate state, for example Othmar Spann (*Der wahre Staat.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] Vorlesungen über Abbruch und Neubau der Gesellschaft*, Vienna, 1921).
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] Müller is the main representative of political romanticism.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] Central to this is his criticism of liberalism and the writings of Adam Smith.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] Philosophically, Müller starts from his theory of opposites - a kind of early dialectic view that revolves around the idea of mediation and balance.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] Müller was a man of great and versatile talents, an excellent orator, and a suggestive writer.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] A critical pamphlet, which was written in 1817 on the occasion of the Protestant jubilee of the Reformation and entitled, *Etwas, das Goethe gesagt hat.
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] Leipzig, den 31 Oktober 1817*, was printed but not published (reprinted in Vienna, 1910).
[src:alfred-dregger/adam-müller] Nevertheless, Traugott Krug's reply, entitled *Etwas, das Herr Adam Müller gesagt hat über etwas, das Goethe gesagt hat, und noch etwas, das Luther gesagt hat* (Leipzig, 1817), appeared in two editions.
[src:alfred-dregger/addresses-to-the-german-nation] Fichte evoked a sense of German distinctiveness in language, tradition, and literature that composed the identity of a nation (people).
[src:alfred-dregger/addresses-to-the-german-nation] According to Bertrand Russell in his *History of Western Philosophy*, Fichte's work laid the theoretical foundations of German nationalism.
[src:alfred-dregger/adelheid-d-tröscher] She attended grammar school and high school in Ithaca, New York, United States, graduating in 1959.
[src:alfred-dregger/adelheid-d-tröscher] She then studied education, history and English language and literature in Marburg, Jugenheim an der Bergstraße and Frankfurt am Main and passed her first and second state examinations to become a teacher at secondary schools.
[src:alfred-dregger/adelheid-d-tröscher] In 1962 she was accepted into the teaching profession and from 1975 to 1976 she worked in the school department of the Regierungspräsidium Darmstadt.
[src:alfred-dregger/adelheid-d-tröscher] From 1986 to 1992, she was head of the Paul Hindemith Comprehensive School in Frankfurt am Main.
[src:alfred-dregger/adelheid-d-tröscher] After leaving the parliamentary group in the Bundestag of her own accord, she became involved in the SPD on a voluntary basis, particularly in the *Forum One World*, which deals with development policy issues.
[src:alfred-dregger/adelheid-d-tröscher] She also heads the Rhine-Main regional group of Transparency International.
[src:alfred-dregger/adelheid-d-tröscher] She is also involved as chairwoman of the Citoyen Foundation, which supports civic engagement and is particularly concerned with the artistic and aesthetic education of children and young people.
[src:alfred-dregger/adelheid-d-tröscher] Tröscher is the daughter of Tassilo Tröscher.
[src:alfred-dregger/adelheid-d-tröscher] From 1972 to 1977, from 1981 to 1989 and in 1991 she was a city councillor of the city of Frankfurt am Main, and from 1992 to 1993 a full-time district councillor of the Kreis Offenbach.
[src:alfred-dregger/adelheid-d-tröscher] From November 1994 to October 2002, Tröscher was a member of the German Bundestag for two terms.
[src:alfred-dregger/adelheid-d-tröscher] In the 1994 Bundestag election, she entered parliament via the SPD state list, and in the 1998 Bundestag election she won the direct mandate in the constituency 144 (Odenwald).
[src:alfred-dregger/adelheid-d-tröscher] From 1994 to 2002, she was a member of the Committee on Economic Cooperation and Development and from 1996 to 2002, she was the SPD parliamentary group's spokesperson on development policy.
[src:alfred-dregger/adelheid-d-tröscher] Tröscher is a member of GEW, AWO, Kinderschutzbund, Pro Familia and medico international.
[src:alfred-dregger/adelheid-d-tröscher] In 1999 she became a member of the board of trustees and the administrative committee of Deutsche Stiftung für internationale Entwicklung (DSE) and a member of German Foundation for International Development.
[src:alfred-dregger/adelheid-d-tröscher] (DSE) and a member of German Agro Action.
[src:alfred-dregger/alfred-dregger] After graduating from a school in Werl, he entered the German Wehrmacht in 1939.
[src:alfred-dregger/alfred-dregger] He was wounded four times and served until the end of the war, when he commanded a battalion on the Eastern Front at the rank of Captain.
[src:alfred-dregger/alfred-dregger] In 1946, he began studying law and government at the universities of Marburg and Tübingen, earning his doctorate in 1950.
[src:alfred-dregger/alfred-dregger] Dregger served from 1956 to 1970 as *Oberbürgermeister* or mayor of Fulda; when first elected, he was the youngest mayor in West Germany.
[src:alfred-dregger/alfred-dregger] He also served from 1962 to 1972 as a member of the Landtag of Hesse.
[src:alfred-dregger/alfred-dregger] He was for a time leader of the CDU in that body, and, in 1967, became state party chairman, an office which he held until 1982.
[src:alfred-dregger/alfred-dregger] In 1969 he was also elected as a member of the national board of the party.
[src:alfred-dregger/alfred-dregger] From 1972 1998 he was a representative in the German Bundestag; from 1982 to 1991 he was Chairman of the CDU/CSU group there.
[src:alfred-dregger/alfred-dregger] Dregger was known as a staunch conservative and was a prominent member of the so-called Stahlhelm-Fraktion, a National-Conservative wing of the CDU.
[src:alfred-dregger/alfred-dregger] In the 1970s he was an outspoken proponent of outlawing the German Communist Party.
[src:alfred-dregger/alfred-dregger] He was responsible for the slogan "Freiheit statt Sozialismus" (Freedom instead of Socialism) with which the CDU had great success in the 1976 elections.
[src:alfred-dregger/alfred-dregger] In his eulogy, German Chancellor Friedrich Merz said of him, "Few have so clearly and categorically opposed the Left for decades".
[src:alfred-dregger/alfred-dregger] He called for Germany to "come out of Hitler's shadow".
[src:alfred-dregger/alfred-dregger] Alfred Dregger was married and had two sons; his elder son was killed in an accident in 1972.
